<br>
1. New Leadership and/or they've lowered their standards and will take anyone. <br>
<br>
or:<br>
<br>
2. They really need the class he plays and find ways to justify why it's a great idea to have a Vah Shir named Morris DeCat in the guild. Which I guess is just a by-product of lowering their standards.<br>
<br>
That's how I look on it. But what really matters is how your guildmates feel about having this person in the guild. It is my feeling that if a guildmate is highly uncomfortable with a possible recruit into the guild, for whatever reason, than that recruit should not be considered, assuming you actually want to keep that guildmember in your guild. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tobrin>Tobrin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Big Guy says I'm<br>
12 short of a Dozen! </span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/28/03 10:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3580.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Personal character vs roleplay standards</span><hr size=1> I rather liked the comment someone made about fitting the name into the character's story.<br>
<br>
If your character was named, say, RapMasta or ThisBook, something more of a phrase or real-life oriented ooc name, then that's a bit harder to justify.<br>
<br>
But names that are more borderline such as Ankles (someone mentioned this one), Grog, or even something like Horn can have a story behind it that doesn't stretch the boundaries of Norrathian life too far.  Many characters in stories have nicknames given to them regarding something they have done or something that was a hallmark of them.<br>
<br>
Other names are more neutral and fit in better with a fantasy theme.  Names like Larallin, Malief, or something else abstract like that.  Even &quot;common&quot; names like Anna or Cedric still make sense.  Heck, I wouldn't be too disturbed if someone went by the name of Alec, Beth, or something like that; peasant names were often short and simple.  Where do you think &quot;modern&quot; names like Sally, Andrew, and the sort originated?<br>
<br>
Anyway, that's just my thoughts.  And like others have hinted at, if you're a serious roleplayer, you'd get rather irritated sporting a horribly ooc name like GeikoGecko (*wince*). <p>Tobrin &lt;Crusaders of Thunder&gt;<br>
